At the time of the explosion
of the event horizons,

00:26:17.840 --> 00:26:21.780 align:middle line:84%
these images were ejected
onto both sides of the shroud,

00:26:21.780 --> 00:26:25.740 align:middle line:84%
with the body hovering
parallel to the event horizons.

00:26:25.740 --> 00:26:29.080 align:middle line:84%
This explains why the
image shows a dead man, not

00:26:29.080 --> 00:26:30.530 align:middle line:90%
the risen body.

00:26:30.530 --> 00:26:33.620 align:middle line:84%
It also explains why
the image is negative.

00:26:33.620 --> 00:26:37.130 align:middle line:84%
It went from a positive body
image to the negative image,

00:26:37.130 --> 00:26:39.390 align:middle line:90%
like a camera film negative.

00:26:39.390 --> 00:26:44.380 align:middle line:84%
This indicates how the
image got onto the cloth.

00:26:44.380 --> 00:26:51.470 align:middle line:10%
To Piczek, the shroud symbolizes
life, or victory over death.

00:26:51.470 --> 00:26:55.140 align:middle line:10%
It does not signify
the end of Jesus' life.

00:26:55.140 --> 00:26:58.930 align:middle line:84%
Rather, it is an
unbelievable beginning

00:26:58.930 --> 00:27:02.400 align:middle line:84%
of his new life because of the
depth of the collapsed event

00:27:02.400 --> 00:27:03.680 align:middle line:90%
horizon.

00:27:03.680 --> 00:27:07.250 align:middle line:84%
There is the
singularity, she says.

00:27:07.250 --> 00:27:12.010 align:middle line:84%
This is what physicist proposed
happened at the Big Bang.

00:27:12.010 --> 00:27:13.600 align:middle line:84%
And she says that
we have nothing

00:27:13.600 --> 00:27:16.950 align:middle line:84%
less in the tomb of
Christ that the beginning

00:27:16.950 --> 00:27:20.890 align:middle line:90%
of a new universe.

00:27:20.890 --> 00:27:23.950 align:middle line:84%
In his article that lays out
his considered reflections

00:27:23.950 --> 00:27:28.110 align:middle line:84%
on the question of how a man
can shine brighter than the Sun,

00:27:28.110 --> 00:27:30.570 align:middle line:84%
Doctor Andrew Silverman
begins with the evidence

00:27:30.570 --> 00:27:35.830 align:middle line:84%
that thought, light, and
matter are interrelated.

00:27:35.830 --> 00:27:38.620 align:middle line:84%
It is further suggested that
the nature of this relation

00:27:38.620 --> 00:27:41.770 align:middle line:84%
implies that our
corporeal state is

00:27:41.770 --> 00:27:45.640 align:middle line:84%
a symptom of the
restriction of mind.

00:27:45.640 --> 00:27:47.990 align:middle line:84%
And inference, says
Silverman, derives

00:27:47.990 --> 00:27:52.200 align:middle line:84%
from this that simply undoing
these restrictions has

00:27:52.200 --> 00:27:57.200 align:middle line:84%
the power to release the tension
of space, which we call matter,

00:27:57.200 --> 00:28:03.020 align:middle line:84%
thereby transforming
it into light.

00:28:03.020 --> 00:28:05.950 align:middle line:84%
Silverman cites the argument
that Erwin Schrodinger

00:28:05.950 --> 00:28:09.100 align:middle line:84%
made, one of the founders
of quantum theory.

00:28:09.100 --> 00:28:12.410 align:middle line:84%
He says that the eternal
nature of consciousness

00:28:12.410 --> 00:28:15.090 align:middle line:90%
is the answer to the question.

00:28:15.090 --> 00:28:18.770 align:middle line:84%
If Schrodinger was correct,
then all sentient beings

00:28:18.770 --> 00:28:22.490 align:middle line:84%
must have been one in the
initial singularity which

00:28:22.490 --> 00:28:24.680 align:middle line:90%
gave rise to the Big Bang.

00:28:24.680 --> 00:28:29.230 align:middle line:84%
This all-together state of
sentience beyond time and space

00:28:29.230 --> 00:28:32.160 align:middle line:84%
precedes the state of
separation and limitation

00:28:32.160 --> 00:28:36.360 align:middle line:90%
that define a physical universe.

00:28:36.360 --> 00:28:40.040 align:middle line:84%
In my view, this state
is the primordial state,

00:28:40.040 --> 00:28:43.870 align:middle line:84%
or perfect state, of
the great perfection.

00:28:43.870 --> 00:28:47.200 align:middle line:90%
So how do we return there?

00:28:47.200 --> 00:28:50.770 align:middle line:10%
Silverman again,
"since separation

00:28:50.770 --> 00:28:53.280 align:middle line:10%
is the hallmark
of limit, it would

00:28:53.280 --> 00:28:59.310 align:middle line:10%
follow that the exhortation to
love thy neighbor as thyself

00:28:59.310 --> 00:29:02.420 align:middle line:10%
is simply a route
map for returning

00:29:02.420 --> 00:29:06.700 align:middle line:10%
to our original status."

00:29:06.700 --> 00:29:11.070 align:middle line:10%
In his Easter address in
2009, Pope Benedict XVI

00:29:11.070 --> 00:29:16.220 align:middle line:10%
said, "Indeed, one of the
questions that most preoccupies

00:29:16.220 --> 00:29:21.150 align:middle line:10%
men and women is this:
what is there after death?"

00:29:21.150 --> 00:29:23.460 align:middle line:84%
To this mystery,
today's solemnity

00:29:23.460 --> 00:29:26.930 align:middle line:84%
allows us to respond
that death does not

00:29:26.930 --> 00:29:32.660 align:middle line:84%
have the last word, because life
will be victorious at the end.

00:29:32.660 --> 00:29:36.650 align:middle line:84%
This certainty of ours is based
not on simple human reasoning,

00:29:36.650 --> 00:29:39.800 align:middle line:84%
but on a historical
fact of faith.

00:29:39.800 --> 00:29:41.950 align:middle line:10%
Jesus Christ
crucified and buried

00:29:41.950 --> 00:29:46.380 align:middle line:10%
is risen with his glorified
body, his rainbow body.

00:29:46.380 --> 00:29:48.860 align:middle line:10%
Jesus has risen so
that we, too, believing

00:29:48.860 --> 00:29:51.330 align:middle line:10%
in him may have eternal life.

00:29:51.330 --> 00:29:55.420 align:middle line:10%
This proclamation is at the
heart of the gospel message.

00:29:55.420 --> 00:29:57.510 align:middle line:10%
And as Saint Paul
vigorously declares,

00:29:57.510 --> 00:30:00.880 align:middle line:10%
"If Christ has not been raised,
our preaching is in vain,

00:30:00.880 --> 00:30:03.710 align:middle line:10%
and your faith is in vain."

00:30:03.710 --> 00:30:07.170 align:middle line:84%
"The resurrection,
then, is not a theory

00:30:07.170 --> 00:30:10.560 align:middle line:84%
but a historical reality
revealed by the man

00:30:10.560 --> 00:30:13.700 align:middle line:84%
Jesus Christ by means
of his pass over,

00:30:13.700 --> 00:30:19.410 align:middle line:84%
his passage, that has opened
a new way between heaven

00:30:19.410 --> 00:30:21.770 align:middle line:90%
and earth," said the Pope.

00:30:21.770 --> 00:30:23.930 align:middle line:90%
It is neither a myth nor dream.

00:30:23.930 --> 00:30:26.440 align:middle line:90%
It is not a vision or a utopia.

00:30:26.440 --> 00:30:27.680 align:middle line:90%
It is not a fairy tale.

00:30:27.680 --> 00:30:31.500 align:middle line:84%
But it is a singular, a
singularity if you will,

00:30:31.500 --> 00:30:35.150 align:middle line:90%
and unrepeatable event.

00:30:35.150 --> 00:30:38.080 align:middle line:84%
Jesus of Nazareth, son of
Mary, who at dusk on Friday

00:30:38.080 --> 00:30:40.290 align:middle line:84%
was taken down from
the cross and buried,

00:30:40.290 --> 00:30:42.800 align:middle line:90%
has victoriously left the tomb.

00:30:42.800 --> 00:30:45.610 align:middle line:84%
In fact, at dawn on the
first day after the Sabbath,

00:30:45.610 --> 00:30:48.070 align:middle line:84%
Peter and John found
the tomb empty.

00:30:48.070 --> 00:30:50.430 align:middle line:84%
Mary Magdalene and
the other women

00:30:50.430 --> 00:30:53.700 align:middle line:90%
encountered the risen Jesus.

00:30:53.700 --> 00:30:55.900 align:middle line:84%
On the way to Emmaus,
the two disciples

00:30:55.900 --> 00:30:58.460 align:middle line:84%
recognized him at the
breaking of the bread.

00:30:58.460 --> 00:31:01.060 align:middle line:84%
The risen one appeared
to the Apostles

00:31:01.060 --> 00:31:03.220 align:middle line:84%
that evening in the
upper room, and then

00:31:03.220 --> 00:31:06.270 align:middle line:84%
to many other
disciples in Galilee.

00:31:06.270 --> 00:31:07.800 align:middle line:84%
The Pope concluded
his statement,

00:31:07.800 --> 00:31:10.490 align:middle line:84%
saying that by a
new and living way,

00:31:10.490 --> 00:31:15.360 align:middle line:84%
he opened through the
curtain that is his body.

00:31:15.360 --> 00:31:20.160 align:middle line:84%
To me, the Pope is pointing
us at the secret of arcanum.

00:31:20.160 --> 00:31:22.690 align:middle line:84%
He's telling us that
the Shroud of Turin

00:31:22.690 --> 00:31:26.860 align:middle line:84%
is in fact an open portal
or gateway into the Heavenly

00:31:26.860 --> 00:31:31.340 align:middle line:84%
realms, and that it's in fact
an invitation for us to open

00:31:31.340 --> 00:31:35.300 align:middle line:84%
that portal within our
own hearts and our lives.

00:31:35.300 --> 00:31:37.170 align:middle line:84%
We conclude with
the words of Jesus

00:31:37.170 --> 00:31:40.190 align:middle line:84%
and the Pistis Sophia
when he said, "Cease not

00:31:40.190 --> 00:31:42.440 align:middle line:84%
to seek day and
night, and remit not

00:31:42.440 --> 00:31:46.800 align:middle line:84%
yourselves until you find
the purifying mysteries that

00:31:46.800 --> 00:31:50.500 align:middle line:84%
will purify you, and make
you into a refined light,

00:31:50.500 --> 00:31:52.940 align:middle line:84%
so that you will go
on height and inherit

00:31:52.940 --> 00:31:54.990 align:middle line:90%
the light of my kingdom."

00:31:54.990 --> 00:31:59.450 align:middle line:90%
That is the secret of arcanum.

00:31:59.450 --> 00:32:01.310 align:middle line:84%
In Clare's Beyond
the Veil segment,

00:32:01.310 --> 00:32:04.670 align:middle line:84%
she'll take us into the
minds of visionary artists

00:32:04.670 --> 00:32:07.190 align:middle line:84%
who are inspired by
the Shroud of Turin.

00:32:07.190 --> 00:32:17.600 align:middle line:90%


00:32:17.600 --> 00:32:20.880 align:middle line:84%
>>CLARE: One may venture to
say that the Shroud of Turin

00:32:20.880 --> 00:32:23.380 align:middle line:84%
would have to be on
many people's list

00:32:23.380 --> 00:32:28.260 align:middle line:84%
as the top 10 artifacts to
be treasured by the world.

00:32:28.260 --> 00:32:31.930 align:middle line:84%
It truly is very
special, indeed.

00:32:31.930 --> 00:32:36.920 align:middle line:84%
In 2010, William and I made
a pilgrimage to Turin, Italy,

00:32:36.920 --> 00:32:40.370 align:middle line:84%
to experience the Shroud
of Turin personally.

00:32:40.370 --> 00:32:46.190 align:middle line:84%
I use the word experience,
because we believe it is real.

00:32:46.190 --> 00:32:49.330 align:middle line:84%
We wanted to study
and connect with it,

00:32:49.330 --> 00:32:53.580 align:middle line:84%
and we did in a very
powerful and memorable way.

00:32:53.580 --> 00:33:00.400 align:middle line:84%
In fact, once encountered,
never forgotten.

00:33:00.400 --> 00:33:03.660 align:middle line:10%
We arrived at the chapel
of John the Baptist

00:33:03.660 --> 00:33:07.850 align:middle line:10%
and were greeted by a long,
snaking line of fellow pilgrims

00:33:07.850 --> 00:33:11.770 align:middle line:10%
in a silent procession
toward the cathedral.

00:33:11.770 --> 00:33:16.560 align:middle line:84%
We were very intrigued by
the stations of powerful art

00:33:16.560 --> 00:33:20.590 align:middle line:90%
that we passed along the way.

00:33:20.590 --> 00:33:24.540 align:middle line:10%
they very clearly gave the
Church's view of the shroud

00:33:24.540 --> 00:33:26.623 align:middle line:10%
as an icon of resurrection.

00:33:26.623 --> 00:33:31.580 align:middle line:90%


00:33:31.580 --> 00:33:34.600 align:middle line:10%
Here we see Christ
carrying the cross,

00:33:34.600 --> 00:33:39.530 align:middle line:10%
and encountering Veronica, upon
whose veil the face of Christ

00:33:39.530 --> 00:33:42.640 align:middle line:10%
was said to be imprinted.

00:33:42.640 --> 00:33:47.380 align:middle line:84%
Along the way, we caught a peek
at the magnificent, spiraling

00:33:47.380 --> 00:33:50.990 align:middle line:90%
stupa atop the Shrouded Chapel.

00:33:50.990 --> 00:33:56.020 align:middle line:90%


00:33:56.020 --> 00:34:00.600 align:middle line:84%
This is the beautiful Sun Gate
symbolism inside this stupa.

00:34:00.600 --> 00:34:03.460 align:middle line:90%


00:34:03.460 --> 00:34:05.530 align:middle line:84%
The inner sanctum
of the cathedral

00:34:05.530 --> 00:34:09.130 align:middle line:84%
where the shroud lies,
when on public display,

00:34:09.130 --> 00:34:13.000 align:middle line:84%
captures the essence
of the shroud itself.

00:34:13.000 --> 00:34:15.545 align:middle line:84%
As we both sat silently
in front of the shroud

00:34:15.545 --> 00:34:18.260 align:middle line:84%
in quiet reflection
on the magnitude

00:34:18.260 --> 00:34:23.310 align:middle line:84%
of this priceless and
holy icon of Jesus,

00:34:23.310 --> 00:34:26.949 align:middle line:84%
I thought the many
individuals over time

00:34:26.949 --> 00:34:29.860 align:middle line:84%
who had encountered
visions of Jesus,

00:34:29.860 --> 00:34:33.900 align:middle line:84%
and even painted what they
saw with a clear likeness

00:34:33.900 --> 00:34:35.820 align:middle line:90%
to the face on the shroud.

00:34:35.820 --> 00:34:38.429 align:middle line:90%


00:34:38.429 --> 00:34:42.880 align:middle line:84%
William and I both had visions
of a golden being of light

00:34:42.880 --> 00:34:45.370 align:middle line:84%
while sitting in
quiet contemplation

00:34:45.370 --> 00:34:50.380 align:middle line:84%
in the seated area right in
front of the shroud itself.

00:34:50.380 --> 00:34:54.580 align:middle line:84%
We believe to this day it
was the spirit of Christ.

00:34:54.580 --> 00:35:00.550 align:middle line:84%
And this incredible icon
is indeed authentic.

00:35:00.550 --> 00:35:04.440 align:middle line:84%
The Bible does not give a
physical description of Jesus.

00:35:04.440 --> 00:35:09.620 align:middle line:84%
Why do people believe the
face on the shroud is Jesus?

00:35:09.620 --> 00:35:13.950 align:middle line:10%
The answer is the
crown of thorns.

00:35:13.950 --> 00:35:16.870 align:middle line:10%
The Bible describes
the mocking of Jesus

00:35:16.870 --> 00:35:19.190 align:middle line:10%
before his crucifixion.

00:35:19.190 --> 00:35:21.780 align:middle line:10%
Part of this mocking
included the placement

00:35:21.780 --> 00:35:25.300 align:middle line:10%
of a crown of
thorns on his head.

00:35:25.300 --> 00:35:29.560 align:middle line:84%
This was not done to
other crucifixion victims.

00:35:29.560 --> 00:35:32.230 align:middle line:84%
The shroud shows
evidence of wounds

00:35:32.230 --> 00:35:37.230 align:middle line:84%
from sharp, spark-like spark--
The shroud shows evidence

00:35:37.230 --> 00:35:41.190 align:middle line:84%
of wounds from sharp,
spike-like objects

00:35:41.190 --> 00:35:43.870 align:middle line:90%
around the top of his head.

00:35:43.870 --> 00:35:46.780 align:middle line:84%
Shroud experts believe
a crown of thorns

00:35:46.780 --> 00:35:49.860 align:middle line:84%
is the source of the
blood flows on the head

00:35:49.860 --> 00:35:53.990 align:middle line:84%
of the man in the
Shroud of Turin.

00:35:53.990 --> 00:35:58.300 align:middle line:84%
Further evidence that the face
on the shroud belongs to Jesus

00:35:58.300 --> 00:36:02.290 align:middle line:84%
comes from an examination of
the development of Christian art

00:36:02.290 --> 00:36:04.900 align:middle line:90%
portraying Jesus.

00:36:04.900 --> 00:36:08.500 align:middle line:84%
This wall painting,
found in 1921

00:36:08.500 --> 00:36:12.900 align:middle line:84%
in a house church at
Dura-Europos, Syria,

00:36:12.900 --> 00:36:16.520 align:middle line:84%
is the earliest known
representation of Jesus

00:36:16.520 --> 00:36:21.910 align:middle line:90%
dating from about 235 AD.

00:36:21.910 --> 00:36:24.720 align:middle line:84%
It is now part of the
Dura-Europos collection

00:36:24.720 --> 00:36:30.970 align:middle line:84%
at the Yale University
Gallery of Fine Arts, USA.

00:36:30.970 --> 00:36:34.520 align:middle line:84%
This third-century fresco
of the Good Shepherd

00:36:34.520 --> 00:36:37.720 align:middle line:84%
was found on the ceiling
of the vault of Lucina

00:36:37.720 --> 00:36:40.185 align:middle line:84%
in the catacomb of
Callixtus in Rome.

00:36:40.185 --> 00:36:43.060 align:middle line:90%


00:36:43.060 --> 00:36:45.400 align:middle line:84%
The image of Jesus
as the Good Shepherd

00:36:45.400 --> 00:36:47.590 align:middle line:84%
was an especially
popular motive in

00:36:47.590 --> 00:36:49.790 align:middle line:90%
the early Christian centuries.

00:36:49.790 --> 00:36:52.740 align:middle line:84%
It was based on several
biblical passages,

00:36:52.740 --> 00:36:57.540 align:middle line:84%
including the 23rd Psalm
and sayings of Jesus,

00:36:57.540 --> 00:37:03.040 align:middle line:84%
and is also an adaption
of a popular pagan image.

00:37:03.040 --> 00:37:08.510 align:middle line:84%
These third- to fourth-century
images of Jesus as a magician

00:37:08.510 --> 00:37:12.690 align:middle line:84%
are from Roman sarcophagi,
now in the Vatican museum.

00:37:12.690 --> 00:37:15.280 align:middle line:90%


00:37:15.280 --> 00:37:18.900 align:middle line:10%
This sixth-century mosaic
now in the British Museum

00:37:18.900 --> 00:37:21.630 align:middle line:10%
is from Dorset, England.

00:37:21.630 --> 00:37:27.310 align:middle line:10%
Jesus still resembles
Apollo or Helios.

00:37:27.310 --> 00:37:29.230 align:middle line:10%
After the
sixth-century discovery

00:37:29.230 --> 00:37:33.120 align:middle line:10%
of the Shroud of Turin in
Edessa, images of Jesus

00:37:33.120 --> 00:37:35.740 align:middle line:10%
became full frontal
facial images

00:37:35.740 --> 00:37:39.990 align:middle line:10%
with many of the features
seen on the shroud.

00:37:39.990 --> 00:37:44.630 align:middle line:10%
At Ravenna's Sant'appollinare
Nuovo Church,

00:37:44.630 --> 00:37:49.780 align:middle line:10%
we find this sixth-century
mosaic of Christ enthroned

00:37:49.780 --> 00:37:53.110 align:middle line:10%
as the Heavenly King.

00:37:53.110 --> 00:37:57.590 align:middle line:10%
Suddenly in the sixth century,
the features of Christ in art

00:37:57.590 --> 00:38:01.910 align:middle line:10%
were brought into focus, as
if by an invisible decree,

00:38:01.910 --> 00:38:04.210 align:middle line:10%
says Ian Wilson.

00:38:04.210 --> 00:38:08.630 align:middle line:84%
The hair became long and center
parted, the beard established

00:38:08.630 --> 00:38:12.950 align:middle line:84%
and forked, the nose
longer and more pronounced,

00:38:12.950 --> 00:38:17.070 align:middle line:84%
the eyes deeper,
the pupils larger.

00:38:17.070 --> 00:38:18.990 align:middle line:84%
There is an authority
about it that

00:38:18.990 --> 00:38:23.620 align:middle line:84%
seems to suggest that
someone, somewhere, suddenly

00:38:23.620 --> 00:38:26.940 align:middle line:90%
knew what Jesus had looked like.

00:38:26.940 --> 00:38:30.730 align:middle line:84%
If the face on the
shroud inspired this art,

00:38:30.730 --> 00:38:32.235 align:middle line:84%
it happened in
the sixth century.

00:38:32.235 --> 00:38:35.160 align:middle line:90%


00:38:35.160 --> 00:38:37.640 align:middle line:84%
This sixth-century
hammered silver vase

00:38:37.640 --> 00:38:40.380 align:middle line:84%
was discovered
among church ruins

00:38:40.380 --> 00:38:45.720 align:middle line:90%
at Homs ancient Emesa in Syria.

00:38:45.720 --> 00:38:50.750 align:middle line:84%
This is one of the most famous
Christ pantocrator icons.

00:38:50.750 --> 00:38:54.820 align:middle line:84%
It is found at St. Catharine's
monastery in the Sinai,

00:38:54.820 --> 00:38:59.970 align:middle line:84%
and is believed to
date from about 550 AD.

00:38:59.970 --> 00:39:02.140 align:middle line:84%
It is widely thought
to have been sourced

00:39:02.140 --> 00:39:06.050 align:middle line:84%
from the image on
the Shroud of Turin.

00:39:06.050 --> 00:39:09.890 align:middle line:84%
Interesting observation
of this precious icon

00:39:09.890 --> 00:39:14.880 align:middle line:84%
is the symbol on the book
Jesus holds in his left arm.

00:39:14.880 --> 00:39:19.670 align:middle line:84%
The symbol is of the Chintamani,
the wish-fulfilling jewel,

00:39:19.670 --> 00:39:22.690 align:middle line:84%
within both Hindu and
Buddhist traditions.

00:39:22.690 --> 00:39:25.710 align:middle line:84%
It is equivalent to
the Philosopher's Stone

00:39:25.710 --> 00:39:26.870 align:middle line:90%
in Western alchemy.

00:39:26.870 --> 00:39:29.600 align:middle line:90%


00:39:29.600 --> 00:39:34.810 align:middle line:84%
In 1902, Paul Vignon, a French
scholar and early student

00:39:34.810 --> 00:39:39.750 align:middle line:84%
of the shroud, identified
several common characteristics

00:39:39.750 --> 00:39:43.580 align:middle line:84%
of early artistic
pictures of Jesus.

00:39:43.580 --> 00:39:48.640 align:middle line:84%
These characteristics emerged
starting in the sixth century,

00:39:48.640 --> 00:39:50.470 align:middle line:84%
about the time
that the shroud was

00:39:50.470 --> 00:39:53.980 align:middle line:84%
found hidden high in
a wall of the city.

00:39:53.980 --> 00:39:58.940 align:middle line:10%
These are all, to some degree,
found on the Shroud of Turin.

00:39:58.940 --> 00:40:02.360 align:middle line:10%
The Vignon markings, as
they have come to be called,

00:40:02.360 --> 00:40:06.470 align:middle line:10%
all appear on the shroud as
part of the image of the man--

00:40:06.470 --> 00:40:09.630 align:middle line:10%
or as anomalies, in the cloth.

00:40:09.630 --> 00:40:12.410 align:middle line:90%


00:40:12.410 --> 00:40:16.460 align:middle line:84%
Vignon paid particular attention
to an eight-century Christ

00:40:16.460 --> 00:40:21.920 align:middle line:84%
pantocrator, from the catacomb
of Saint Ponteneau, Rome.

00:40:21.920 --> 00:40:24.840 align:middle line:84%
It cannot be later than
the eighth century,

00:40:24.840 --> 00:40:29.750 align:middle line:84%
because the catacomb was
closed down in 820 AD,

00:40:29.750 --> 00:40:34.470 align:middle line:90%
and only reopened in 1852.

00:40:34.470 --> 00:40:36.630 align:middle line:84%
On the forehead
between the eyebrows

00:40:36.630 --> 00:40:40.010 align:middle line:84%
of this work, a
starkly geometrical,

00:40:40.010 --> 00:40:43.000 align:middle line:90%
U shape caught his eye.

00:40:43.000 --> 00:40:47.520 align:middle line:84%
He found the same
marking on the shroud.

00:40:47.520 --> 00:40:52.270 align:middle line:84%
Vignon found the same U shape,
and the shroud likeness,

00:40:52.270 --> 00:40:56.970 align:middle line:84%
in the Christ pantocrator
from the 11th century dome

00:40:56.970 --> 00:41:00.720 align:middle line:84%
of the Church of
Daphne near Athens.

00:41:00.720 --> 00:41:04.780 align:middle line:10%
Clearly shown are
two wisps of hair

00:41:04.780 --> 00:41:09.910 align:middle line:10%
in the center of the forehead,
hair on one side of the head

00:41:09.910 --> 00:41:14.400 align:middle line:10%
shorter than on
the other side, a U

00:41:14.400 --> 00:41:17.530 align:middle line:10%
shape between the
eyebrows-- often

00:41:17.530 --> 00:41:21.885 align:middle line:10%
square-bottomed-- a
downward-pointing triangle or V

00:41:21.885 --> 00:41:29.770 align:middle line:10%
on the bridge of the nose, and
one raised eyebrow, large round

00:41:29.770 --> 00:41:34.080 align:middle line:10%
eyes accents on both
cheeks somewhat lower

00:41:34.080 --> 00:41:38.440 align:middle line:10%
the right cheek, a
forked beard, a gap

00:41:38.440 --> 00:41:41.100 align:middle line:10%
in the beard below
the lower lip,

00:41:41.100 --> 00:41:47.610 align:middle line:10%
and an enlarged left nostril,
an accent line below the nose,

00:41:47.610 --> 00:41:51.950 align:middle line:10%
and a dark line just
below the lower lip.

00:41:51.950 --> 00:41:54.996 align:middle line:84%
The theory is that
the Shroud of Turin,

00:41:54.996 --> 00:41:59.320 align:middle line:84%
then the Image of Edessa,
was the original inspiration

00:41:59.320 --> 00:42:03.360 align:middle line:84%
for various works of
art with these markings.

00:42:03.360 --> 00:42:05.880 align:middle line:84%
These images prove
the shroud was

00:42:05.880 --> 00:42:08.560 align:middle line:84%
in existence in
the sixth century,

00:42:08.560 --> 00:42:11.120 align:middle line:84%
and is not a
12th-century forgery.

00:42:11.120 --> 00:42:13.850 align:middle line:90%


00:42:13.850 --> 00:42:16.830 align:middle line:84%
Wilson points to this
10th-century example

00:42:16.830 --> 00:42:21.040 align:middle line:84%
of the shroud likeness--
the Christ-enthroned fresco

00:42:21.040 --> 00:42:28.560 align:middle line:84%
in the Church of Sant'Angelo
in Formis near Capua, Italy.

00:42:28.560 --> 00:42:31.970 align:middle line:84%
This late 11th-century
Romanesque fresco

00:42:31.970 --> 00:42:36.550 align:middle line:84%
of Christ pantocrator
in Novalesa Abbey

00:42:36.550 --> 00:42:40.670 align:middle line:84%
shows the Vignon markings
and the triple dot Chintamani

00:42:40.670 --> 00:42:42.960 align:middle line:90%
symbol.

00:42:42.960 --> 00:42:46.910 align:middle line:84%
From the 12th century, there
is an excellent example

00:42:46.910 --> 00:42:51.270 align:middle line:84%
in the Christ pantocrator
mosaic in the apse of the Norman

00:42:51.270 --> 00:42:57.330 align:middle line:84%
Byzantine church
of Cefalu, Sicily.

00:42:57.330 --> 00:43:03.140 align:middle line:84%
In 1978, historian
Ian Wilson pointed out

00:43:03.140 --> 00:43:06.900 align:middle line:84%
that the pray manuscript
was one of a small number

00:43:06.900 --> 00:43:11.300 align:middle line:84%
of 11th to 12th century
deposition scenes.

00:43:11.300 --> 00:43:14.240 align:middle line:84%
For example, depictions
of Christ's descent

00:43:14.240 --> 00:43:17.740 align:middle line:84%
from the cross--
that was strongly

00:43:17.740 --> 00:43:22.050 align:middle line:84%
reminiscent of the Shroud of
Turin in that they depicted

00:43:22.050 --> 00:43:26.780 align:middle line:84%
the dead Christ being laid onto
a large, double-length piece

00:43:26.780 --> 00:43:32.170 align:middle line:84%
of linen intended to envelop
his body over his head,

00:43:32.170 --> 00:43:38.110 align:middle line:84%
with his hands crossed in
front, right hand over the left,

00:43:38.110 --> 00:43:41.250 align:middle line:90%
as on the shroud.

00:43:41.250 --> 00:43:44.330 align:middle line:10%
This likeness can be
found in the 13th century

00:43:44.330 --> 00:43:48.945 align:middle line:10%
mosaic of Christ enthroned
in the gallery of Hagia

00:43:48.945 --> 00:43:57.080 align:middle line:10%
Sophia, Constantinople,
and also in the DC mosaic

00:43:57.080 --> 00:43:57.925 align:middle line:10%
at Hagia Sophia.

00:43:57.925 --> 00:44:01.540 align:middle line:90%


00:44:01.540 --> 00:44:07.800 align:middle line:84%
Finally, in the 15th century,
we find one ideal work of art

00:44:07.800 --> 00:44:10.690 align:middle line:84%
with which to compare
the shroud image.

00:44:10.690 --> 00:44:16.220 align:middle line:84%
This is none other than Jan
Van Eyck and his Rex Regnum.

00:44:16.220 --> 00:44:19.210 align:middle line:84%
Although the original
has not survived,

00:44:19.210 --> 00:44:21.520 align:middle line:84%
it is known to us
from four copies

00:44:21.520 --> 00:44:24.350 align:middle line:90%
that were made at that time.

00:44:24.350 --> 00:44:27.340 align:middle line:84%
It has the same rigidly
front-facing aspect

00:44:27.340 --> 00:44:29.130 align:middle line:90%
of the shroud face.

00:44:29.130 --> 00:44:33.710 align:middle line:84%
Other distinctive features
that match the shroud exactly

00:44:33.710 --> 00:44:37.700 align:middle line:84%
include: long hair
parted in the middle

00:44:37.700 --> 00:44:42.140 align:middle line:84%
and falling to the shoulders,
moderately long forked

00:44:42.140 --> 00:44:47.190 align:middle line:84%
beard, long prominent
nose, thin mustache

00:44:47.190 --> 00:44:52.480 align:middle line:84%
drooping to join the beard, a
hairless gap beneath the lower

00:44:52.480 --> 00:44:54.650 align:middle line:90%
lip.

00:44:54.650 --> 00:44:56.500 align:middle line:84%
As Wilson says,
it might have been

00:44:56.500 --> 00:44:59.870 align:middle line:90%
copied from the shroud face.

00:44:59.870 --> 00:45:05.420 align:middle line:84%
Did Jan van Eyck have
access to the shroud?

00:45:05.420 --> 00:45:07.890 align:middle line:84%
Art experts say
Van Eyck derived it

00:45:07.890 --> 00:45:10.690 align:middle line:84%
from Christ
portraits of the East

00:45:10.690 --> 00:45:15.040 align:middle line:84%
from Byzantium, in which
artists routinely copied

00:45:15.040 --> 00:45:20.130 align:middle line:84%
the same likeness of Christ
from an earlier source.

00:45:20.130 --> 00:45:24.120 align:middle line:84%
Might Van Eyck have had a
vision of the man in the shroud?

00:45:24.120 --> 00:45:27.270 align:middle line:90%


00:45:27.270 --> 00:45:30.510 align:middle line:10%
Van Eyck's painting of
the resurrected Christ

00:45:30.510 --> 00:45:37.080 align:middle line:10%
in a halo of rainbow light
is also based on the shroud.

00:45:37.080 --> 00:45:41.575 align:middle line:84%
But again, is it possible Van
Eyck saw this face in a vision,

00:45:41.575 --> 00:45:42.075 align:middle line:90%
too?

00:45:42.075 --> 00:45:44.640 align:middle line:90%


00:45:44.640 --> 00:45:47.740 align:middle line:84%
Heinrich Kaufmann
was one such painter,

00:45:47.740 --> 00:45:51.990 align:middle line:84%
who captured the image of Jesus
in his many religious works

00:45:51.990 --> 00:45:56.070 align:middle line:90%
of art in the late 1800s.

00:45:56.070 --> 00:46:02.850 align:middle line:84%
Another artist was Turkish-born
Ariel Pascal Agemian

00:46:02.850 --> 00:46:07.850 align:middle line:84%
who studied in Venice throughout
Italy, France, and America.

00:46:07.850 --> 00:46:14.670 align:middle line:84%
It was in 1935 that he painted
the well-known "Face of Christ"

00:46:14.670 --> 00:46:18.060 align:middle line:84%
based on the negative
of the Shroud of Turin,

00:46:18.060 --> 00:46:21.220 align:middle line:84%
receiving accolade
from science experts,

00:46:21.220 --> 00:46:27.420 align:middle line:84%
and eventually awarded a gold
medal from Pope Pius XII,

00:46:27.420 --> 00:46:30.910 align:middle line:84%
and knighted into the order
of Saint Gregory the Great.

00:46:30.910 --> 00:46:33.930 align:middle line:90%


00:46:33.930 --> 00:46:37.310 align:middle line:10%
Another visionary
artist alive today

00:46:37.310 --> 00:46:40.340 align:middle line:10%
is Nanette Christ,
whose ancestors

00:46:40.340 --> 00:46:45.310 align:middle line:10%
were icon painters of the
Eastern Orthodox church.

00:46:45.310 --> 00:46:50.450 align:middle line:10%
Nanette's beautiful painting
of Christ is world famous,

00:46:50.450 --> 00:46:55.120 align:middle line:10%
and has touched millions
of people in their lives.

00:46:55.120 --> 00:46:58.600 align:middle line:84%
She writes about the
extraordinary manifestation

00:46:58.600 --> 00:47:01.080 align:middle line:84%
of this beautiful
painting, that she

00:47:01.080 --> 00:47:05.300 align:middle line:84%
was directed to paint
from her sacred vision.

00:47:05.300 --> 00:47:10.610 align:middle line:84%
It was on the Thursday
before Easter in 1986,

00:47:10.610 --> 00:47:15.680 align:middle line:84%
when she had prayed before easel
before beginning a painting.

00:47:15.680 --> 00:47:20.140 align:middle line:84%
Suddenly, she experienced
a clear vision

00:47:20.140 --> 00:47:25.270 align:middle line:84%
of the presence of Jesus
standing beside the easel

00:47:25.270 --> 00:47:29.770 align:middle line:90%
and bathed in very bright light.

00:47:29.770 --> 00:47:35.780 align:middle line:84%
Nanette described Jesus'
face with a gentle strength,

00:47:35.780 --> 00:47:42.340 align:middle line:84%
beautiful, penetrating gray-blue
eyes, and light auburn hair,

00:47:42.340 --> 00:47:46.010 align:middle line:90%
and wearing a pearly-white robe.

00:47:46.010 --> 00:47:48.270 align:middle line:90%
His chest was broad.

00:47:48.270 --> 00:47:54.030 align:middle line:84%
He was quite tall, she writes,
with a perfect posture.

00:47:54.030 --> 00:47:59.950 align:middle line:84%
Nanette was asked by
Jesus to paint his image

00:47:59.950 --> 00:48:06.330 align:middle line:84%
in his likeness, so that
everyone who believed in him

00:48:06.330 --> 00:48:10.810 align:middle line:84%
and loved him would be
able to look into his eyes

00:48:10.810 --> 00:48:13.830 align:middle line:90%
and connect to his soul.

00:48:13.830 --> 00:48:16.630 align:middle line:84%
The painting took
Nanette three days,

00:48:16.630 --> 00:48:20.160 align:middle line:84%
and she completed
it on Easter Sunday.

00:48:20.160 --> 00:48:23.290 align:middle line:84%
The final masterpiece
was authenticated

00:48:23.290 --> 00:48:25.030 align:middle line:84%
by the visionaries
of the Catholic

00:48:25.030 --> 00:48:29.250 align:middle line:90%
Church and other faiths.

00:48:29.250 --> 00:48:31.590 align:middle line:84%
Could the shroud have
been left for mankind

00:48:31.590 --> 00:48:37.080 align:middle line:84%
for this very reason, for
man to connect and remember

00:48:37.080 --> 00:48:44.730 align:middle line:84%
the message that Jesus left us
all; to live in his footsteps

00:48:44.730 --> 00:48:49.510 align:middle line:90%
under the canopy of pure love?

00:48:49.510 --> 00:48:52.120 align:middle line:84%
As we have seen,
the shroud has been

00:48:52.120 --> 00:48:57.180 align:middle line:84%
a subject of immense
fascination, if not obsession,

00:48:57.180 --> 00:49:00.990 align:middle line:84%
with history's greatest
visionary artists.

00:49:00.990 --> 00:49:04.040 align:middle line:84%
One can only wonder
how future visionary

00:49:04.040 --> 00:49:08.050 align:middle line:90%
artists will portray the shroud.

00:49:08.050 --> 00:49:11.580 align:middle line:84%
Will the visionary mind
develop even further

00:49:11.580 --> 00:49:15.170 align:middle line:84%
in its spiritual evolution,
as the human race

00:49:15.170 --> 00:49:18.610 align:middle line:90%
evolves in the Golden Age?

00:49:18.610 --> 00:49:23.380 align:middle line:84%
In 2013, the shroud
went digital.

00:49:23.380 --> 00:49:27.290 align:middle line:84%
The Shroud 2.0 app was
authorized by the Turin

00:49:27.290 --> 00:49:31.330 align:middle line:84%
archdiocese, and is now
available for downloads

00:49:31.330 --> 00:49:33.430 align:middle line:90%
on iTunes.

00:49:33.430 --> 00:49:37.320 align:middle line:84%
This allows one to explore
the sheet in detail

00:49:37.320 --> 00:49:41.100 align:middle line:84%
through access to an excellent,
high-definition photographic

00:49:41.100 --> 00:49:43.725 align:middle line:84%
document that
offers features that

00:49:43.725 --> 00:49:48.020 align:middle line:84%
are almost invisible to
the naked eye, elements

00:49:48.020 --> 00:49:51.910 align:middle line:84%
that not even the traditional
expositions have ever

00:49:51.910 --> 00:49:54.850 align:middle line:90%
allowed to observe.

00:49:54.850 --> 00:49:58.390 align:middle line:84%
As sacred visionary
art goes digital,

00:49:58.390 --> 00:50:02.210 align:middle line:84%
will this enable people
to connect with the shroud

00:50:02.210 --> 00:50:03.970 align:middle line:90%
more directly?

00:50:03.970 --> 00:50:07.610 align:middle line:84%
Or will it diminish
the connection?

00:50:07.610 --> 00:50:11.432 align:middle line:90%
Time will tell.

00:50:11.432 --> 00:50:12.640 align:middle line:90%
>>WILLIAM: I'm William Henry.

00:50:12.640 --> 00:50:14.650 align:middle line:84%
Thank you for
watching "Arcanum."

00:50:14.650 --> 00:50:15.970 align:middle line:90%
>>CLARE: And I'm Clare Henry.

00:50:15.970 --> 00:50:18.280 align:middle line:90%
See you next time.

